            "title": "Knowledge Graphs: Key to Enhancing the Intelligence of ChatGPT and Other Large Language Models",
            "pubDate": "2023-12-10 13:23:57",
            "link": "https://medium.com/@hoffmann.webdev/knowledge-graphs-key-to-enhancing-the-intelligence-of-chatgpt-and-other-large-language-models-a0a3d19a70fd?source=rss-f854b7a48d24------2",
            "guid": "https://medium.com/p/a0a3d19a70fd",
            "author": "Till Hoffmann",
            "thumbnail": "https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*ve_OtWk71QdHCa-x",
            "description": "\n<p>Large language models (LLMs) like ChatGPT have revolutionized natural language processing with their ability to generate human-like text. However, the biggest weakness of tools like ChatGPT is that they rely on implicit knowledge from their broad training data. This can lead to biased or inaccurate outputs. This excels in areas where up-to-date information is crucial.</p>\n<figure><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*ve_OtWk71QdHCa-x\"><figcaption>Photo by <a href=\"https://unsplash.com/@almosbech?utm_source=medium&amp;utm_medium=referral\">Almos Bechtold</a> on <a href=\"https://unsplash.com/?utm_source=medium&amp;utm_medium=referral\">Unsplash</a></figcaption></figure><h4><strong>The problem of hallucinations in ChatGPT responses.</strong></h4>\n<p>We know hallucinations from psychology, Wikipedia defines them as follows:</p>\n<blockquote>A <strong>hallucination</strong> is a perception in the absence of an external stimulus that has the qualities of a real perception. Hallucinations are vivid, substantial, and are perceived to be located in external objective space.</blockquote>\n<p>A hallucination in the context of LLMs can be understood as something similar — plausible but inaccurate or fictional responses. This occurs because LLMs generate responses based on patterns in their training data rather than relying on verified, factual data.</p>\n<h3>The potential of knowledge graphs in addressing hallucinations</h3>\n<h4>What are knowledge graphs?</h4>\n<p>For this, it is important to understand what a Knowledge Graph is. For that, I recommend one of my previous articles:</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://medium.com/@hoffmann.webdev/unlocking-the-power-of-knowledge-graphs-a-strategic-tool-for-businesses-d438af1d1c1f\">Unlocking the Power of Knowledge Graphs: A Strategic Tool for Businesses</a></p>\n<p>But to summarize it, Knowledge graphs organize and represent data in a network. Each node in this network represents an entity and each edge is a relationship. Therefore, knowledge graphs are highly flexible and represent highly connected data. Usually, knowledge graphs are embedded in an integrated system that gets regular relevant data from previously defined external systems.</p>\n<h4>How can a knowledge graph improve my ChatGPT results?</h4>\n<p>Due to the structured and integrated nature of knowledge graphs, they represent the actual context of the containing entities. By integrating knowledge graphs, LLMs can access and utilize accurate, and up-to-date information, improving the reliability of their outputs. Additionally, it can improve accuracy dramatically in specialized or rapidly changing domains.</p>\n<p>In an ideal world, users can interact with knowledge graphs by simply asking them in natural language — like the interaction with ChatGPT. To implement this, there are 4 steps to follow to implement a technology like that:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Use natural language processing to understand the requests of the user.</li>\n<li>Generate a query, to query the knowledge graph.</li>\n<li>Use the data from the knowledge graph to feed it into ChatGPT and provide the initial question to generate a meaningful answer.</li>\n<li>Display the answer to the user.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Use natural language processing to understand the requests of the user.</strong></p>\n<p>Imagine this system is implemented in a big company and an employee wants to find out which colleague is responsible for a specific customer.</p>\n<blockquote>Which colleague is responsible for the customer super-comp?</blockquote>\n<p>A natural language processing pipeline can now<strong> </strong>identify the main entities and their relations by using techniques like tokenizing, tagging, named entity recognition, and dependency parsing. The visualization of a result can look like the following:</p>\n<figure><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/1*Z71KCPd8C9zL_9rJ11wgaA.jpeg\"></figure><p><strong>Generate a query, to query the knowledge graph.</strong></p>\n<p>Depending on the implementation and technology used for the knowledge graph this step can differ. Generally, a knowledge graph will be implemented in some kind of database which can be queried.</p>\n<p>We can use tokens from the question to build a concrete query for the database. The concrete process for that can be different based on the use case but one should try to use at least two or more tokens from the initial question to provide as much context as possible. Those tokens get imbedded into a query which is then sent to the database.</p>\n<p><strong>Use the data from the knowledge graph to feed it into ChatGPT and provide the initial question to generate a meaningful answer.</strong></p>\n<p>The result of the previous step is some form of structured data in the best case. In the worst case, if no data was found, we can tell the user, that we did not find an answer to that question. Let's assume we found some data, that can be used as content for our ChatGPT query. Additionally, we should also provide the initial question, so we can advise ChatGPT to formulate a relevant response.</p>\n<p><strong>Display the answer to the user.</strong></p>\n<p>The last step is probably the most easy and obvious, providing the answer to the user. Ideally, the response contains some references to resources where the user can verify the given answer and continue the work. For this specific use case some contact details of the colleague and maybe some link to the CRM system where the user can verify the answer.</p>\n<h3>Outlook</h3>\n<p>Overall, integrating knowledge graphs with ChatGPT can help to overcome some of the inherent limitations of LLMs, leading to a more accurate, reliable, and context-aware AI system. This approach can streamline the organization and retrieval of the amount of company knowledge.</p>\n<p>For companies considering this solution and technology, it is worth evaluating different solutions. For many companies options like ChatGPT can not be suitable for compliance and data privacy-sensitive reasons. Furthermore, ChatGPT might also be too powerful, cost-intensive, and complex for that use case, alternative LLMs that can be run locally might already suit the needs of this use case.</p>\n<p>This strategic approach to selecting and implementing knowledge graph-based solutions, tailored to the unique requirements and constraints of each business, is key to unlocking the full potential of AI in enhancing internal knowledge management.</p>\n<p>LinkedIn: <a href=\"https://www.linkedin.com/in/tillhoffmann/\">https://www.linkedin.com/in/tillhoffmann/</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.till-hoffmann.me/\">Till Hoffmann</a></p>\n<img src=\"https://medium.com/_/stat?event=post.clientViewed&amp;referrerSource=full_rss&amp;postId=a0a3d19a70fd\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" alt=\"\">\n",
